instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin lifecycle follows a Model‑Based Systems‑Engineering (MBSE) approach that is split into several abstraction levels: (1) requirements modeling, (2) functional architecture, (3) logical architecture, and (4) product/technical (physical) layer. During development the twin is first represented by high‑level SysML requirement and block diagrams, then refined into functional and logical models using architecture description languages such as ACME, AADL, MontiArc or SysML internal block diagrams, and finally instantiated with concrete engineering, simulation or data‑calculation models (e.g., Simulink). Transition between stages is governed by explicit traceability links (the “originates‑from” association) that connect data traces to the processing components and the models that generated them, ensuring that each refinement step can be audited and that governance of the lifecycle is based on conformance to the Digital Shadow Reference Model."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity and validity are addressed through traceability and verification of model transformations. The reliability of a digital shadow (and by extension a Digital Twin) is directly linked to the correctness of its underlying models and the data‑processing steps; therefore, verification methods such as systematic checks of transformations from SysML to simulation models are employed. Uncertainty sources include errors in the original data traces and inaccuracies in the physics‑based (white‑box) or data‑driven (black‑box) models; these are quantified by maintaining fine‑grained traceability, which allows the origin of any computed trace to be identified and inspected. Error detection is supported by the “originates‑from” association that enables back‑propagation of inconsistencies, and correction mechanisms rely on re‑executing processing components with validated input. Quality assurance is ensured by conforming concrete realizations to the Digital Shadow Reference Model, guaranteeing that all modeling concepts and their relationships satisfy the defined conformance relation."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The Digital Twin framework adopts several industry modelling standards: SysML (OMG) for requirements and behavior models, AADL (SAE) for architecture description, ACME for component‑connector specifications, MontiArcAutomaton for combined architecture and automaton behavior, and Simulink (MathWorks) for simulation models. Conformance to the Digital Shadow Reference Model is achieved through a defined conformance relation that maps concrete class diagrams to the reference concepts, ensuring interoperability across tools and adherence to the referenced standards."
]
